00:06:13.530 --> 00:06:17.460
So you started learning
at the age of three.

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:19.670
Is there anything you
remember from that time?

00:06:19.670 --> 00:06:21.086
ZAKIR HUSSAIN:
Well, first of all,

00:06:21.086 --> 00:06:26.740
I don't think I started actually
learning at the age of three.

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:30.790
I don't think I really had
a say in when I actually

00:06:30.790 --> 00:06:31.690
started learning.

00:06:31.690 --> 00:06:33.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:33.720 --> 00:06:36.290
You're in a music home,
you're in a musician's home,

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:39.235
you're in a drummer's house, and
he happens to be your father.

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:44.240
From the day you're
brought in from the nursing

00:06:44.240 --> 00:06:49.740
home where you were born,
you really are inducted.

00:06:49.740 --> 00:06:50.890
You don't have a choice.

00:06:50.890 --> 00:06:53.790
And so it was the same with me.

00:06:53.790 --> 00:06:56.630
What happened with me was
when I was brought home,

00:06:56.630 --> 00:06:59.490
I think the second
day after I was born,

00:06:59.490 --> 00:07:01.900
and they hadn't yet
chosen a name for me.

00:07:01.900 --> 00:07:04.480
So it was Baby Qureshi.

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:06.020
That's our family, Qureshi.

00:07:06.020 --> 00:07:08.510
So could have been
male, female, whatever.

00:07:08.510 --> 00:07:10.360
They weren't sure.

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:15.010
Anyway, so even nowadays, I
sit in an airplane in a seat,

00:07:15.010 --> 00:07:16.890
and a stewardess comes
from here and says,

00:07:16.890 --> 00:07:18.640
can I get you something, ma'am?

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:20.225
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:20.225 --> 00:07:21.600
It's got something
to do with it.

00:07:21.600 --> 00:07:22.550
I don't know.

00:07:22.550 --> 00:07:29.170
So I was brought home, handed
up to my dad in his arm,

00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:32.970
and the tradition
was, OK, the father

00:07:32.970 --> 00:07:37.540
is supposed to recite a
prayer in the baby's ear

00:07:37.540 --> 00:07:41.350
welcoming the baby and
put in some good words.

00:07:41.350 --> 00:07:45.980
So he takes me in his arm,
puts his lips to my ear,

00:07:45.980 --> 00:07:49.320
and recites rhythms.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:52.450
He did, [SINGING RHYTHMS]
And my mother was livid.

00:07:52.450 --> 00:07:54.140
She said, what are you doing?

00:07:54.140 --> 00:07:58.970
You're supposed to say
prayers, not these rhythms.

00:07:58.970 --> 00:08:01.740
And he said, but
these are my prayers.

00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:03.270
This is how I pray.

00:08:03.270 --> 00:08:06.990
He said, I am the worshipper
of Goddess Saraswati,

00:08:06.990 --> 00:08:08.590
Lord Ganesha.

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:11.380
And this is a devout
Muslim talking.

00:08:11.380 --> 00:08:14.950
And this is the
knowledge, or [INAUDIBLE],

00:08:14.950 --> 00:08:16.810
I got from my teachers.

00:08:16.810 --> 00:08:18.510
And I want to pass
it on to my son.

00:08:18.510 --> 00:08:20.980
He is going to do exactly this.

00:08:20.980 --> 00:08:25.720
So why not start him early
and give him these prayers?

00:08:25.720 --> 00:08:30.100
So that's what I mean when
I say inducted already.

00:08:30.100 --> 00:08:31.250
I had no say in it.

00:08:31.250 --> 00:08:36.270
Like it or not, you're not going
to hear [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:08:36.270 --> 00:08:36.809
or whatever.

00:08:36.809 --> 00:08:40.620
You're going to actually
hear [SINGING RHYTHMS]

00:08:40.620 --> 00:08:42.419
and like it or not.

00:08:42.419 --> 00:08:45.530
So from there on, I think
it was his routine every day

00:08:45.530 --> 00:08:51.350
to sit for an hour or so or
two singing rhythms in my ear.

00:08:51.350 --> 00:08:55.748
And the way he held me, this
ear was closed, so it stayed in.

00:08:55.748 --> 00:09:00.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:00.430 --> 00:09:04.750
So anyway, those went
in, so by the time

00:09:04.750 --> 00:09:09.710
I was three when I could
actually reach the tabla

00:09:09.710 --> 00:09:16.570
and had hands slightly bigger
to get on to the tabla,

00:09:16.570 --> 00:09:18.200
I already had all
this information

00:09:18.200 --> 00:09:21.640
in my head and this
big jumbled confusion,

00:09:21.640 --> 00:09:23.810
which I had really no
idea what to do with.

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:29.900
And so that's when the tabla
was put in front of me.

00:09:29.900 --> 00:09:33.320
And I started to hit it.

00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:37.010
And at that point,
my father decided

00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:39.860
to use reverse psychology.

00:09:39.860 --> 00:09:42.240
So now instead of putting
rhythms in my ear,

00:09:42.240 --> 00:09:44.600
he just disappeared.

00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:48.440
It's like, OK, no more
learning or hearing

00:09:48.440 --> 00:09:53.540
those nice little things which
put me to sleep, none of that.

00:09:53.540 --> 00:09:57.240
I was suddenly having
to fend for myself.

00:09:57.240 --> 00:10:00.100
And I guess his
whole plan was not

00:10:00.100 --> 00:10:04.520
to overdose me with this stuff
so I would just go away and not

00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:05.630
want it.

00:10:05.630 --> 00:10:08.570
It was more like giving
me a little taste of it,

00:10:08.570 --> 00:10:12.200
and then he pulled back to see
what I was going to do with it.

00:10:12.200 --> 00:10:16.440
And at that age, I was
being put on a spot

00:10:16.440 --> 00:10:22.630
to make a decision, to
commit to this or whatever.

00:10:22.630 --> 00:10:26.550
And so I guess my--
what should I say?

00:10:26.550 --> 00:10:32.580
The feelings or my instinct
brought me to commit to it.

00:10:32.580 --> 00:10:37.210
And I started playing with it,
and if I didn't have the tabla,

00:10:37.210 --> 00:10:41.940
I would see my mother's pots
and turn them around and play.

00:10:41.940 --> 00:10:44.320
Once or twice I did it
with the food in it.

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:46.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:46.110 --> 00:10:49.360
So you know what that did.

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:54.070
So anyway, that's how it all
began at the age of three

00:10:54.070 --> 00:10:57.120
till when I was seven.

00:10:57.120 --> 00:10:59.990
I rarely saw my dad.

00:10:59.990 --> 00:11:02.350
I'm sure he was
lurking about, looking

00:11:02.350 --> 00:11:05.600
to see what I was doing,
whether I was interested or not.

00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:07.980
But it was mostly his students
who would occasionally

00:11:07.980 --> 00:11:10.250
show me or do this or do that.

00:11:10.250 --> 00:11:13.150
And they would speak something,
and I would already know it,

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:14.626
because it was already here.

00:11:14.626 --> 00:11:17.000
And then it was a matter of
just putting on to the drums,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.080
so it started becoming easy.

00:11:19.080 --> 00:11:22.960
But once I was about
seven years old,

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:25.680
I had already started
doing school concerts,

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:30.200
playing in my school things,
inauguration day, this day,

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:31.250
that day.

00:11:31.250 --> 00:11:35.180
So on one of those occasions,
he came to the school

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:37.540
to hear me play.

00:11:37.540 --> 00:11:41.620
And I played, and that was
done and after that went home.

00:11:41.620 --> 00:11:44.460
And at dinner, he
says to me, do you

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:47.470
want to study this seriously?

00:11:47.470 --> 00:11:51.310
And I jumped at it, because
this man, being with him

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:53.510
and having him there, so
I said, yes, of course.

00:11:53.510 --> 00:11:55.990
So he said, OK,
tomorrow we're start.

00:11:55.990 --> 00:11:59.160
So that was a very
exciting night for me,

00:11:59.160 --> 00:12:02.030
except for it ended early.

00:12:02.030 --> 00:12:04.970
He woke me up at 3:00 AM.

00:12:04.970 --> 00:12:06.330
I was seven years old.

00:12:06.330 --> 00:12:10.960
And so when everybody
slept and it was quiet,

00:12:10.960 --> 00:12:16.730
no phones ringing, no nothing,
we sat like this on our veranda

00:12:16.730 --> 00:12:20.730
and spoke rhythms and talked
about the masters, talked

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:25.030
about this great tradition
and where it came from

00:12:25.030 --> 00:12:27.890
and what it represented
and the importance of it

00:12:27.890 --> 00:12:31.580
and the reverence that it
requires et cetera, et cetera,

00:12:31.580 --> 00:12:32.220
et cetera.

00:12:32.220 --> 00:12:35.720
And for the next few years,
that became the routine

00:12:35.720 --> 00:12:37.210
for a seven-year-old.

00:12:37.210 --> 00:12:40.570
Get up at 3:00 AM, sit
with him till 6:00,

00:12:40.570 --> 00:12:43.730
have breakfast, get
ready, go to school,

00:12:43.730 --> 00:12:50.020
but on the way to school,
detour to the madrasa,

00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:54.960
learn to recite the Quran,
and then cross the street

00:12:54.960 --> 00:12:59.760
and assemble in the St.
Michael's high school church

00:12:59.760 --> 00:13:05.150
and sing the hymns and then
go to the classroom and start

00:13:05.150 --> 00:13:09.730
learning, come home, and
then after lunch practice.

00:13:09.730 --> 00:13:11.180
So that became the routine.

00:13:11.180 --> 00:13:17.970
So I went to a confusing, for
many people-- being connected

00:13:17.970 --> 00:13:22.930
to Lord Ganesha and Lord Shiva
and Krishna and Saraswato

00:13:22.930 --> 00:13:29.380
from between 3:00 and 6:00 AM
and then between 7:00 and 7:45

00:13:29.380 --> 00:13:33.970
dealing with the Quran and
from 8:00 to about 8:20

00:13:33.970 --> 00:13:36.530
dealing with the church and
the hymns and the psalms

00:13:36.530 --> 00:13:39.090
and so on and then,
of course, going

00:13:39.090 --> 00:13:41.910
to school and then the tabla.

00:13:41.910 --> 00:13:43.780
But what was
interesting about that

00:13:43.780 --> 00:13:53.210
was none of these institutions
ever imposed their will on me

00:13:53.210 --> 00:13:55.850
or any of my fellow students.

00:13:55.850 --> 00:14:00.770
It appeared to be a
natural thing to do.

00:14:00.770 --> 00:14:03.540
It felt like a
normal thing to do.

00:14:03.540 --> 00:14:06.630
It wasn't like, OK,
I was doing something

00:14:06.630 --> 00:14:10.100
that the mullahs in the
neighborhood would not like

00:14:10.100 --> 00:14:15.040
or something that
the pundits will ban

00:14:15.040 --> 00:14:16.500
or whatever, none of that.

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:21.680
And I was not made to feel
like I should do this and not

00:14:21.680 --> 00:14:23.470
that, do that and not that.

00:14:23.470 --> 00:14:25.160
It all appeared to
be part of one thing,

00:14:25.160 --> 00:14:28.050
as it is, as it should be.

00:14:28.050 --> 00:14:31.490
I mean, neither the Bible
or the Torah or the Quran

00:14:31.490 --> 00:14:34.800
or the Gita or
Ramayana, whatever, none

00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:37.280
has said anything different.

00:14:37.280 --> 00:14:40.050
They've all said
love thy neighbor.

00:14:40.050 --> 00:14:44.300
And that's basically
the gist of it.

00:14:44.300 --> 00:14:47.170
And it appeared to be
that way in my childhood.

00:14:47.170 --> 00:14:51.930
So I grew up, married my
wife Toni, who is here.

00:14:51.930 --> 00:14:55.290
We had three ceremonies.

00:14:55.290 --> 00:14:58.807
I have to give three wedding
anniversary presents.

00:14:58.807 --> 00:15:01.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:01.550 --> 00:15:03.210
Life is not easy,
I'm telling you.

00:15:03.210 --> 00:15:05.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:05.510 --> 00:15:08.000
So we first did
the civil marriage.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.990
Then we did the church
wedding because the family.

00:15:12.990 --> 00:15:15.560
And then to appease
my father and mother,

00:15:15.560 --> 00:15:17.970
we did the Muslim
nikah ceremony,

00:15:17.970 --> 00:15:20.890
so in three different
time of the year.

00:15:20.890 --> 00:15:25.100
If it would have happened on one
day, it would have been easy.

00:15:25.100 --> 00:15:27.520
But now I have to remember
three wedding anniversary

00:15:27.520 --> 00:15:32.890
dates on three different times
of the year and all that.

00:15:32.890 --> 00:15:35.680
And that and my
kids being baptized

00:15:35.680 --> 00:15:42.250
and all that, it has not
felt that I'm struggling

00:15:42.250 --> 00:15:48.020
to have all these thought
processes in any way

00:15:48.020 --> 00:15:49.680
co-exist in my mind.

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:51.460
And this comes from
in the childhood

00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:54.500
being exposed to all of
this as something normal.

00:15:54.500 --> 00:15:58.050
And it was same with my music.

00:15:58.050 --> 00:16:02.590
Everybody says 2,000-year-old
history and you have to play 20

00:16:02.590 --> 00:16:07.260
hours a day for 20 years and
then you might be able to get

00:16:07.260 --> 00:16:09.390
some sound out of
the instrument.

00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:14.130
I think that's pure
BS, but that's just me.

00:16:14.130 --> 00:16:18.210
But I was never subjected
to that kind of thinking.

00:16:18.210 --> 00:16:21.380
I was always like, OK,
do it, and it's normal,

00:16:21.380 --> 00:16:23.600
it's fun, take it easy.

00:16:23.600 --> 00:16:27.900
So without the pressure,
I was able to study.

00:16:27.900 --> 00:16:31.720
So there were different
periods from day two

00:16:31.720 --> 00:16:34.780
till three, ding, ding,
ding, ding, ding, ding,

00:16:34.780 --> 00:16:37.720
ding; from three to seven,
pat, pat, pat, boom, boom,

00:16:37.720 --> 00:16:40.430
boom pat-pat, ch-ch-chh,
all that stuff.

00:16:40.430 --> 00:16:43.830
And then from seven
onward, really

00:16:43.830 --> 00:16:47.870
getting involved into the mantra
with my dad in the mornings

00:16:47.870 --> 00:16:49.960
and then studying.

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:54.120
And then up till about the
age of 11 or 12, that carried.

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:58.700
And then I played my first
professional concert in India

00:16:58.700 --> 00:17:02.970
at the age of 12,
got 100 rupees, man.

00:17:02.970 --> 00:17:05.859
You could buy a lot of
carrot halwah with that.

00:17:05.859 --> 00:17:09.119
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:09.119 --> 00:17:12.160
Many gulab jamuns
later, I said, oops,

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:14.280
I should bring some of
this leftover money home,

00:17:14.280 --> 00:17:15.505
shouldn't I?

00:17:15.505 --> 00:17:17.130
VINOD MARUR: Well,
now we know a couple

00:17:17.130 --> 00:17:19.420
of your favorite desserts at
least for your next visit here.

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:19.960
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: Wow.

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:20.459
Good.

00:17:20.459 --> 00:17:21.952
Thank you.

00:17:21.952 --> 00:17:24.160
VINOD MARUR: So you mentioned
your wife, who is here.

00:17:24.160 --> 00:17:25.609
Thank you so much
for joining us.

00:17:25.609 --> 00:17:27.234
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: And
my daughter is here.

00:17:27.234 --> 00:17:29.570
VINOD MARUR: Yeah, your
daughter, too, Isabella.

00:17:29.570 --> 00:17:31.065
How did you all meet?

00:17:31.065 --> 00:17:32.530
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: How did we meet?

00:17:32.530 --> 00:17:35.010
Well, there was this
Jack in the Box.

00:17:35.010 --> 00:17:39.480
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:42.950
No, actually, I don't know
if it was meant to be,

00:17:42.950 --> 00:17:47.660
but it just so happens that my
first-ever concert in America

00:17:47.660 --> 00:17:51.890
was in a concert hall in New
York called Fillmore East.

00:17:51.890 --> 00:17:54.230
We have a Fillmore
West here in the city

00:17:54.230 --> 00:17:57.550
next to the dosa place.

00:17:57.550 --> 00:18:01.430
Anyway, so Fillmore
East, and that

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:05.240
happen to be with
Pandit Ravi Shankar.

00:18:05.240 --> 00:18:08.920
I came in, because my
father was not feeling well,

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:11.240
and so he was not
able to make it.

00:18:11.240 --> 00:18:13.430
And I just happened to
be next door in Germany.

00:18:16.020 --> 00:18:19.430
And believe me, in those
days for an 18-year-old,

00:18:19.430 --> 00:18:20.880
it was a piece of cake.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:24.000
Walk into the American Embassy,
give them your passport, say,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.080
I want a visa to go to America.

00:18:26.080 --> 00:18:28.380
Oh, no problem.

00:18:28.380 --> 00:18:30.590
10 minutes later, you
have your passport,

00:18:30.590 --> 00:18:32.480
nothing like, do
you have a ticket?

00:18:32.480 --> 00:18:34.480
You have somebody who's
going to look after you?

00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:36.170
Where are your
bank balance sheets

00:18:36.170 --> 00:18:40.270
and all that-- nothing, none of
that stuff and your appointment

00:18:40.270 --> 00:18:42.590
letters, none of that.

00:18:42.590 --> 00:18:46.260
So he said, come over from
Munich and play with me.

00:18:46.260 --> 00:18:51.600
So I went to the embassy, got
the visa, arrived in New York.

00:18:51.600 --> 00:18:53.220
There's another story to that.

00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:58.580
But that was my first concert,
and it was on February 22.

00:18:58.580 --> 00:19:03.590
And that is my wife's birthday,
my first-ever concert.

00:19:03.590 --> 00:19:04.880
So maybe it was destined.

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:06.340
Maybe, I don't know.

00:19:06.340 --> 00:19:10.100
But I arrived, played
with Ravi Shankar.

00:19:10.100 --> 00:19:12.260
Then I ended up in
University of Washington

00:19:12.260 --> 00:19:15.850
in Seattle as an assistant
professor teaching.

00:19:15.850 --> 00:19:18.120
I was 19 then.

00:19:18.120 --> 00:19:19.670
And so I was teaching there.

00:19:19.670 --> 00:19:22.010
And then out of the blue, I
get a call from [INAUDIBLE]

00:19:22.010 --> 00:19:25.190
Ali Akbar Khan, the
great sarod maestro,

00:19:25.190 --> 00:19:29.050
who has his music college
in Marin, and said,

00:19:29.050 --> 00:19:31.210
my tabla player
has upped and gone.

00:19:31.210 --> 00:19:34.090
Would you come and teach?

00:19:34.090 --> 00:19:38.920
So any tabla player in the
world would give his left leg

00:19:38.920 --> 00:19:40.170
to do that.

00:19:40.170 --> 00:19:41.550
Hands you can't get.

00:19:41.550 --> 00:19:43.920
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:47.080
Or a thumb or like
[INAUDIBLE] or whatever.

00:19:47.080 --> 00:19:52.400
Anyway, so I said yes, and
I gave up my university job

00:19:52.400 --> 00:19:55.560
and came down to
Marin and joined.

00:19:55.560 --> 00:19:58.250
And a few months
later, I was sitting

00:19:58.250 --> 00:20:04.070
in Ali Akbar Khan's living
room, and we were just there.

00:20:04.070 --> 00:20:08.550
And in walks Toni, because she
had heard about the college

00:20:08.550 --> 00:20:12.085
and met a friend of hers who was
going to come to the college,

00:20:12.085 --> 00:20:12.960
et cetera, et cetera.

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:14.390
There is a story there.

00:20:14.390 --> 00:20:17.580
And then she ended up there,
and that's where we met.

00:20:17.580 --> 00:20:21.290
And that night, she
came to see me play.

00:20:21.290 --> 00:20:23.520
And that sealed it, I think.

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:27.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:27.310 --> 00:20:32.770
It's like, OK, he can't speak or
anything, but he sure can play.

00:20:32.770 --> 00:20:36.860
And she actually was impressed
with the dance there.

00:20:36.860 --> 00:20:38.590
There was a dance department.

00:20:38.590 --> 00:20:41.820
And so she started taking
Kathak dance there.

00:20:41.820 --> 00:20:46.180
And then we sort of met
more often, and then

00:20:46.180 --> 00:20:48.130
I asked her out.

00:20:48.130 --> 00:20:53.670
And then she had this great idea
of what Indian musicians are,

00:20:53.670 --> 00:21:01.720
very proper and vegetarians
and all that stuff.

00:21:01.720 --> 00:21:04.110
So on our first date, I
took her to Jack in the Box.

00:21:04.110 --> 00:21:06.260
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:06.260 --> 00:21:09.180
That's all I could afford in
those days, I mean, you know,

00:21:09.180 --> 00:21:10.190
or maybe.

00:21:10.190 --> 00:21:12.490
And then we went into
Sausalito, looked at the moon,

00:21:12.490 --> 00:21:15.010
had an ice cream, and so on.

00:21:15.010 --> 00:21:18.700
But I think what really
clinched it was one night she

00:21:18.700 --> 00:21:21.470
lost her contact lens.

00:21:21.470 --> 00:21:25.230
It was dark on the street out
there, outside on the street.

00:21:25.230 --> 00:21:26.200
And I found it.

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:28.900
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:33.630
[APPLAUSE]

00:21:33.630 --> 00:21:35.410
I mean, you know, there it is.

00:21:35.410 --> 00:21:37.780
Street light is far
away, but I found it.

00:21:37.780 --> 00:21:42.700
And so that really probably
impressed the hell out of her,

00:21:42.700 --> 00:21:43.550
I must say.

00:21:43.550 --> 00:21:46.032
So that's the story of that.

00:21:46.032 --> 00:21:47.740
VINOD MARUR: That is
an incredible story.

00:21:47.740 --> 00:21:49.641
Do you all ever
perform together?

00:21:49.641 --> 00:21:51.890
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: We have
performed quite a lot together.

