00:24:11.630 --> 00:24:13.110
I think about collaboration.

00:24:13.110 --> 00:24:14.844
Can we just roll
the video, please?

00:24:14.844 --> 00:24:15.650
SPEAKER 2: Hi.

00:24:15.650 --> 00:24:16.670
I'm Shruti.

00:24:16.670 --> 00:24:20.080
I work in the Chrome team
here at Google Mountain View.

00:24:20.080 --> 00:24:22.455
Thank you so much for coming
here to speak with us today.

00:24:22.455 --> 00:24:23.580
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: My pleasure.

00:24:23.580 --> 00:24:25.570
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: I am
a huge fan, and I've

00:24:25.570 --> 00:24:27.350
been to many of your concerts.

00:24:27.350 --> 00:24:30.010
I especially love that
you play with musicians

00:24:30.010 --> 00:24:31.790
from different
parts of the world.

00:24:31.790 --> 00:24:34.230
So my question to you
is about collaborating

00:24:34.230 --> 00:24:37.570
with musicians who practice
different styles of music

00:24:37.570 --> 00:24:38.450
than you.

00:24:38.450 --> 00:24:41.910
Do you believe that they
have to share a common vision

00:24:41.910 --> 00:24:44.350
about the music that you
would like to create together?

00:24:44.350 --> 00:24:47.560
Or do you think that given
enough time and mutual respect,

00:24:47.560 --> 00:24:50.360
any two musicians
can create music

00:24:50.360 --> 00:24:52.300
that they both like and enjoy?

00:24:52.300 --> 00:24:54.500
Thank you very much.

00:24:54.500 --> 00:24:57.800
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: OK,
well, there are

00:24:57.800 --> 00:25:02.420
many occasions where musicians
are asked to come together, OK,

00:25:02.420 --> 00:25:07.660
Mr Herbie Hancock, Mr. Chick
Corea, come and play together

00:25:07.660 --> 00:25:13.670
or Shankar Mahadevan
and Shiva Mani

00:25:13.670 --> 00:25:16.940
and Zakir Hussain all
come together and play.

00:25:16.940 --> 00:25:20.670
So those are professional
concerts where you are paid,

00:25:20.670 --> 00:25:23.060
you come, and you play.

00:25:23.060 --> 00:25:26.890
And that can work quite well.

00:25:26.890 --> 00:25:31.620
But I feel up to
a certain extent

00:25:31.620 --> 00:25:37.590
the music that we play has a
lot to do with spontaneity,

00:25:37.590 --> 00:25:41.210
has a lot to do with
instant understanding

00:25:41.210 --> 00:25:43.035
and on-the-fly decision-making.

00:25:45.750 --> 00:25:51.190
For that, you have to know each
other very well on all levels.

00:25:51.190 --> 00:25:53.840
You have to know
the person, what

00:25:53.840 --> 00:25:58.250
his or her dislikes and
likes are in terms of food

00:25:58.250 --> 00:26:02.820
or films or politics or
anything, fashion or whatever,

00:26:02.820 --> 00:26:06.310
apart from that, what
his or her family is like

00:26:06.310 --> 00:26:09.910
and how they relate to music.

00:26:09.910 --> 00:26:16.320
And so I have found over the
years is that I've worked with

00:26:16.320 --> 00:26:20.190
many, many musicians, whether
it's John McLaughlin or Mickey

00:26:20.190 --> 00:26:26.520
Hart or Giovani Hidalgo or
[INAUDIBLE], [INAUDIBLE],

00:26:26.520 --> 00:26:28.710
Shankar Mahadevan, [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:28.710 --> 00:26:32.440
I mean, so many others.

00:26:32.440 --> 00:26:34.490
Some of them, I
have [INAUDIBLE].

00:26:34.490 --> 00:26:36.990
Like I worked with
somebody call Yo-Yo Ma.

00:26:36.990 --> 00:26:38.330
Have you heard of Yo-Yo Ma?

00:26:38.330 --> 00:26:43.160
I was commissioned to write
a piece for him, a bass

00:26:43.160 --> 00:26:45.620
player, a piano
player, and myself

00:26:45.620 --> 00:26:50.190
to play as music to be
choreographed for a dance

00:26:50.190 --> 00:26:56.480
ballet by Mark Morris, a
contemporary ballet composer.

00:26:56.480 --> 00:26:59.100
And so I did.

00:26:59.100 --> 00:27:02.440
But what's interesting
is that that happened,

00:27:02.440 --> 00:27:05.900
and it has not happened again.

00:27:05.900 --> 00:27:08.490
And there may be many reasons.

00:27:08.490 --> 00:27:09.800
I mean, we know each other.

00:27:09.800 --> 00:27:12.880
We still socially
say hello and stuff.

00:27:12.880 --> 00:27:19.820
But that kind of understanding
of knowing each other

00:27:19.820 --> 00:27:23.290
on all layers was
not established

00:27:23.290 --> 00:27:27.460
like it has with, say, banjo
player Bela Fleck or Edgar

00:27:27.460 --> 00:27:31.660
Meyer or John McLaughlin
or Mickey Hart, where we

00:27:31.660 --> 00:27:34.050
know each other inside and out.

00:27:34.050 --> 00:27:36.960
Our families know each
other inside and out.

00:27:36.960 --> 00:27:38.740
We hang out together.

00:27:38.740 --> 00:27:41.670
We exchange recipes together.

00:27:41.670 --> 00:27:44.630
Edgar Meyer calls up and says,
I want to make salmon curry.

00:27:44.630 --> 00:27:46.180
What do I do?

00:27:46.180 --> 00:27:47.666
How much ginger should I have?

00:27:47.666 --> 00:27:49.040
And then I arrive
in his kitchen,

00:27:49.040 --> 00:27:50.456
and there's like
this much ginger.

00:27:53.190 --> 00:27:56.150
And he said, is this enough?

00:27:56.150 --> 00:27:59.580
But anyway, so the thing
is, that is very important.

00:27:59.580 --> 00:28:03.400
Because when you get
on stage, you converse.

00:28:06.170 --> 00:28:09.850
Music, especially
improvised form with music,

00:28:09.850 --> 00:28:13.610
I believe should be spoken like
you speak in English or Hindi

00:28:13.610 --> 00:28:15.920
or French or Italian.

00:28:15.920 --> 00:28:17.290
So it's a language.

00:28:17.290 --> 00:28:22.800
If you can form words,
sentences, paragraphs, whatever

00:28:22.800 --> 00:28:25.700
and tell a story
in that language,

00:28:25.700 --> 00:28:27.510
you are actually improvising.

00:28:27.510 --> 00:28:30.590
Like right now, I'm
improvising in English,

00:28:30.590 --> 00:28:32.690
which is not my first language.

00:28:32.690 --> 00:28:34.980
I did not grow up
learning English.

00:28:34.980 --> 00:28:38.630
So when I finally
came across English,

00:28:38.630 --> 00:28:43.950
I had to master it to a point
where I could improvise in it,

00:28:43.950 --> 00:28:48.050
I could think in it
and spontaneously

00:28:48.050 --> 00:28:50.200
communicate with it.

00:28:50.200 --> 00:28:54.250
So if you can do
that with the music,

00:28:54.250 --> 00:28:58.550
you actually learn how to
improvise, how to be creative.

00:28:58.550 --> 00:28:59.550
That's important.

00:28:59.550 --> 00:29:03.920
So when you're playing with
musicians, that's what you do.

00:29:03.920 --> 00:29:07.450
If I'm playing with
Shankar Mahadevan,

00:29:07.450 --> 00:29:09.900
there would be a look
exchanged, and we'll

00:29:09.900 --> 00:29:12.181
know where we are going next.

00:29:12.181 --> 00:29:13.680
If I'm playing with
John McLaughlin,

00:29:13.680 --> 00:29:15.690
there will be a phrase
played, and I'll

00:29:15.690 --> 00:29:22.590
know a chain of phrases that
we will probably hop across

00:29:22.590 --> 00:29:25.680
and so can anticipate.

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:27.590
Because he's not just playing.

00:29:27.590 --> 00:29:30.190
He's speaking to me.

00:29:30.190 --> 00:29:32.970
So if he's playing
a melodic line,

00:29:32.970 --> 00:29:37.800
he's asking me, how about
going here when we're playing?

00:29:37.800 --> 00:29:41.190
And I'm replaying,
saying, yeah, why not?

00:29:41.190 --> 00:29:43.920
And that has to happen.

00:29:43.920 --> 00:29:49.560
So that intimacy with each other
on all level accomplishes that.

00:29:49.560 --> 00:29:51.240
So that's very
important when you're

00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:54.480
coming into a situation
of playing with musicians

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:58.170
of different genres of
music, even musicians

00:29:58.170 --> 00:29:59.310
of Indian classical music.

00:29:59.310 --> 00:30:03.850
For instance, one of the pieces
that I did before my symphony

00:30:03.850 --> 00:30:06.680
orchestra in London was
with the sitar player,

00:30:06.680 --> 00:30:08.900
[INAUDIBLE] Niladri Kumar.

00:30:08.900 --> 00:30:10.990
We did a duet.

00:30:10.990 --> 00:30:15.180
But we just got on stage, we did
a sound check, and we played.

00:30:15.180 --> 00:30:17.630
We never talked about
what we were going to do.

00:30:17.630 --> 00:30:19.340
But what happens is this.

00:30:19.340 --> 00:30:21.200
You're sitting in
the dressing room,

00:30:21.200 --> 00:30:22.605
and you're talking
about cricket,

00:30:22.605 --> 00:30:24.115
or you're talking
about the weather,

00:30:24.115 --> 00:30:27.020
or you're talking
about politics,

00:30:27.020 --> 00:30:30.770
saying all sorts of things--
Trump, do you believe?

00:30:30.770 --> 00:30:35.530
Or you say all sorts of
funny things to each other.

00:30:35.530 --> 00:30:39.790
And so you kind of are
gauging each other's mood

00:30:39.790 --> 00:30:45.740
at that moment, where one's
mind is at that point.

00:30:45.740 --> 00:30:48.240
And you're talking, and
you're walking onto the stage

00:30:48.240 --> 00:30:50.040
while they are announcing you.

00:30:50.040 --> 00:30:54.290
And then you get on stage
and you start playing.

00:30:54.290 --> 00:31:01.010
But without you knowing, that
talk is now on the instruments.

00:31:01.010 --> 00:31:04.470
And you're speaking,
continuing to speak, as you do.

00:31:04.470 --> 00:31:06.620
When you go to a
concert, sometimes

00:31:06.620 --> 00:31:08.830
find a way into
the dressing room

00:31:08.830 --> 00:31:11.150
and see the musicians
sitting there.

00:31:11.150 --> 00:31:13.410
They are talking
about everything else

00:31:13.410 --> 00:31:15.760
in the world except music.

00:31:15.760 --> 00:31:20.190
Yeah, [INAUDIBLE] and
anything about-- I

00:31:20.190 --> 00:31:22.470
mean, did you hear
what that person said?

00:31:22.470 --> 00:31:23.960
Did you know this happened?

00:31:23.960 --> 00:31:27.750
And what kind of a car I want
to buy and all that stuff.

00:31:27.750 --> 00:31:30.910
Nothing about what
should we be playing,

00:31:30.910 --> 00:31:33.820
can you tell me the melody,
or what rhythm-- nothing.

00:31:33.820 --> 00:31:36.940
And then you go on stage, and
the conversation continues.

00:31:36.940 --> 00:31:37.990
So it's important.

00:31:37.990 --> 00:31:40.260
It doesn't matter
whether you're playing

00:31:40.260 --> 00:31:43.170
with the musicians of
same tradition of music

00:31:43.170 --> 00:31:46.260
that you are from
or other traditions.

00:31:46.260 --> 00:31:50.410
You must intimately
know them well to really

00:31:50.410 --> 00:31:56.000
on all levels interact
and play music, which has

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:59.040
a spark of spontaneity in it.

00:31:59.040 --> 00:32:01.960
Otherwise, you can just
accept a professional gig,

00:32:01.960 --> 00:32:06.660
take a fat check, and just
get together, put together

00:32:06.660 --> 00:32:09.479
a couple of pieces, and get on
stage and play it and go away.

00:32:09.479 --> 00:32:10.312
VINOD MARUR: Got it.

00:32:10.312 --> 00:32:12.200
Cool.

00:32:12.200 --> 00:32:13.710
You mentioned you cook.

00:32:13.710 --> 00:32:15.090
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: Oh, yeah.

00:32:15.090 --> 00:32:17.409
VINOD MARUR: Any
favorite dishes?

00:32:17.409 --> 00:32:19.200
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: Anything
I cook is favorite.

00:32:19.200 --> 00:32:20.325
What are you talking about?

00:32:20.325 --> 00:32:21.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:21.470 --> 00:32:23.490
No, I mean I make good keema.

00:32:23.490 --> 00:32:28.420
I make chicken curry, different
styles of chicken curry.

00:32:28.420 --> 00:32:32.510
I do eggs not bad.

00:32:32.510 --> 00:32:36.050
And so when my daughters
want some Indian,

00:32:36.050 --> 00:32:41.470
they just, hey, Dad, cook up
some chicken curry, will you?

00:32:41.470 --> 00:32:42.710
That happens.

00:32:42.710 --> 00:32:43.860
And so I cook.

00:32:43.860 --> 00:32:48.030
And all musicians are foodies.

00:32:48.030 --> 00:32:48.630
Yeah.

00:32:48.630 --> 00:32:51.420
When they come to the
concert hall, the first thing

00:32:51.420 --> 00:32:54.000
they say to each other, where
are we going for dinner?

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:55.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:55.640 --> 00:32:57.292
Concert hasn't
even happened yet.

00:32:57.292 --> 00:32:58.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:58.470 --> 00:33:01.146
We haven't even opened
our instruments.

00:33:01.146 --> 00:33:03.270
We haven't tuned or anything
or done a sound check.

00:33:03.270 --> 00:33:05.730
The first question is, where
are we going for dinner?

00:33:05.730 --> 00:33:07.880
It's very important.

00:33:07.880 --> 00:33:12.140
I mean, that kind
of expecting allows

00:33:12.140 --> 00:33:15.430
you to get excited about the
journey of getting there.

00:33:15.430 --> 00:33:17.806
And that part of the
journey is playing the music

00:33:17.806 --> 00:33:18.930
and getting that over with.

00:33:18.930 --> 00:33:24.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:24.270 --> 00:33:27.510
VINOD MARUR: Switching
gears a bit, here at Google,

00:33:27.510 --> 00:33:30.210
hard to avoid the
topic of technology.

00:33:30.210 --> 00:33:32.030
What's your sense
about technology,

00:33:32.030 --> 00:33:36.340
how it's affected you, how
you think it's affected music?

00:33:36.340 --> 00:33:39.340
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: Well,
technology has actually

00:33:39.340 --> 00:33:43.360
broadened the way
we think about music

00:33:43.360 --> 00:33:44.725
and we approach our instruments.

00:33:47.710 --> 00:33:51.030
Why, even present
technology-- go back

00:33:51.030 --> 00:33:56.660
85, 90 years to
the sound system,

00:33:56.660 --> 00:33:59.630
the amplification arriving.

00:33:59.630 --> 00:34:04.400
And that was really a
big, landmark happening.

00:34:04.400 --> 00:34:09.630
It really did a lot
to change the way

00:34:09.630 --> 00:34:12.340
we perform music in India.

00:34:12.340 --> 00:34:14.690
And I think it's the same
for music performed anywhere

00:34:14.690 --> 00:34:15.989
in the world.

00:34:15.989 --> 00:34:19.010
I mean, would we have
had stadium concerts

00:34:19.010 --> 00:34:20.750
if there was no sound system?

00:34:20.750 --> 00:34:22.900
No.

00:34:22.900 --> 00:34:23.760
Not at all.

00:34:23.760 --> 00:34:26.760
And would we have had
electric guitars and bass

00:34:26.760 --> 00:34:30.830
guitars and stuff if
there was no sound system?

00:34:30.830 --> 00:34:31.770
No.

00:34:31.770 --> 00:34:34.659
So, I mean, music
has obviously started

00:34:34.659 --> 00:34:39.199
changing from the time when
the sound system arrived.

00:34:39.199 --> 00:34:44.290
Personally speaking
for me, I started

00:34:44.290 --> 00:34:52.989
to discover semitones,
frequencies, microtones,

00:34:52.989 --> 00:34:58.410
resonance, harmonics
in my instrument

00:34:58.410 --> 00:35:01.890
after the mic got put on it.

00:35:01.890 --> 00:35:08.920
And so suddenly, something
which was like pom is now pumm.

00:35:08.920 --> 00:35:13.490
And something that was
boom is now boommm.

00:35:13.490 --> 00:35:18.320
So now suddenly from the
boommm, you can go booommm.

00:35:18.320 --> 00:35:23.660
You can do that, which was
not possible that long ago,

00:35:23.660 --> 00:35:24.660
100 years ago.

00:35:24.660 --> 00:35:29.270
They played music differently--
very hard, very percussive.

00:35:29.270 --> 00:35:31.640
Even the sitar and
the sarod [INAUDIBLE]

00:35:31.640 --> 00:35:33.630
was played very
percussive if you listen

00:35:33.630 --> 00:35:35.970
to a recording 70 years old.

00:35:35.970 --> 00:35:39.690
And something you will notice
is that the change is obvious

00:35:39.690 --> 00:35:40.590
how it is.

00:35:40.590 --> 00:35:44.870
So for me, having
discovered the sound system

00:35:44.870 --> 00:35:47.670
and the frequencies,
I mean, you also

00:35:47.670 --> 00:35:52.530
have to know what frequencies
does the tabla project

00:35:52.530 --> 00:35:56.070
and then how to find
in the sound system

00:35:56.070 --> 00:35:58.900
graphic equalizer,
those frequencies,

00:35:58.900 --> 00:36:00.980
and highlight them.

00:36:00.980 --> 00:36:04.320
So you've got to learn to
recognize all that stuff.

00:36:04.320 --> 00:36:06.520
And then once you
highlight them,

00:36:06.520 --> 00:36:10.400
then you don't have to now bang.

00:36:10.400 --> 00:36:13.110
You don't have to
wallop the instrument.

00:36:13.110 --> 00:36:18.050
You can just play nice and
easy, subtle, too strong,

00:36:18.050 --> 00:36:21.240
whatever you want to do,
and be able to manipulate

00:36:21.240 --> 00:36:25.960
the instrument not just
rhythmically, but melodically.

00:36:25.960 --> 00:36:28.160
And that's what's
happened with the tabla.

00:36:28.160 --> 00:36:30.900
Tabla has now become an
instrument that is not

00:36:30.900 --> 00:36:32.180
just rhythmic instrument.

00:36:32.180 --> 00:36:34.800
It's a melodic
instrument as well.

00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:38.320
And that's invention
of the sound system.

00:36:38.320 --> 00:36:42.880
And then once you've got the
sound system, sky's the limit.

00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:46.830
You can now start putting
Ableton Live on it,

00:36:46.830 --> 00:36:49.170
and you can start
processing the sound.

00:36:49.170 --> 00:36:53.200
You can start putting delays
and whatnot and everything.

00:36:53.200 --> 00:36:56.404
The question is, how
far do you go with it?

00:36:56.404 --> 00:36:58.940
And that's very important.

00:36:58.940 --> 00:37:01.680
I know some friends of
mine who are tabla players,

00:37:01.680 --> 00:37:04.300
like [INAUDIBLE] or
Talvin Singh and all,

00:37:04.300 --> 00:37:07.270
they have electrified
the tablas.

00:37:07.270 --> 00:37:11.960
They have put electronic
pickups into the instrument.

00:37:11.960 --> 00:37:16.370
And they put a cable
under the tabla.

00:37:16.370 --> 00:37:19.470
And they put it through
all these electronic sounds

00:37:19.470 --> 00:37:21.430
and machines.

00:37:21.430 --> 00:37:27.440
And that gives them a whole
range of electronic tones,

00:37:27.440 --> 00:37:30.110
synthetic tones, to work with.

00:37:30.110 --> 00:37:37.970
So, I mean, you can be in some
ways pulled in by that so much

00:37:37.970 --> 00:37:40.740
so that you actually forget what
the real instrument actually

00:37:40.740 --> 00:37:42.440
is.

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:45.440
So I mean, unlike those
gentlemen who have done that

00:37:45.440 --> 00:37:49.090
and have really taken the
tabla into a whole new genre

00:37:49.090 --> 00:37:51.900
of music, which is drum and
bass and [? Asian ?] underground

00:37:51.900 --> 00:37:55.170
and et cetera, et cetera,
and that's a great place,

00:37:55.170 --> 00:37:59.360
I have resisted the
urge of doing that.

00:37:59.360 --> 00:38:04.580
I still play my acoustic tablas
and-- through a microphone,

00:38:04.580 --> 00:38:07.170
of course-- and deal with
the natural tone that

00:38:07.170 --> 00:38:09.160
comes out of that instrument.

00:38:09.160 --> 00:38:15.170
If I want to do electronical
messing with it,

00:38:15.170 --> 00:38:20.500
I have found a system whereby
I have this gear going

00:38:20.500 --> 00:38:23.480
through a computer,
where my microphones go

00:38:23.480 --> 00:38:25.840
through a sound card
into that computer

00:38:25.840 --> 00:38:29.120
so my instrument is not
electronically plugged in.

00:38:29.120 --> 00:38:31.650
That is still acoustic.

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:34.290
So I have a choice
of hitting a button

00:38:34.290 --> 00:38:39.080
and suddenly turning my
tabla into AI, Artificial

00:38:39.080 --> 00:38:43.120
Intelligence, or turning
it off and just playing

00:38:43.120 --> 00:38:44.350
a regular tabla.

00:38:44.350 --> 00:38:51.320
And so that has allowed me
really a lot of leeway and kind

00:38:51.320 --> 00:38:55.440
of a gateway into playing with
a whole different area of music

00:38:55.440 --> 00:38:56.990
and musicians.

00:38:56.990 --> 00:39:01.240
And right now it's under
repairs, my system,

00:39:01.240 --> 00:39:03.860
and they are rebooting it
and upgrading it and so on.

00:39:03.860 --> 00:39:07.700
Once it's done, I'm hoping
to use it again and play

00:39:07.700 --> 00:39:09.110
for composing and stuff.

00:39:09.110 --> 00:39:13.320
I mean, that's what most of the
musicians in India are doing,

00:39:13.320 --> 00:39:14.210
film music.

00:39:14.210 --> 00:39:18.640
They now use a lot
of electronic stuff

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:21.200
to be able to write
music and compose music

00:39:21.200 --> 00:39:25.496
and work at GarageBand is
one of those kind of things,

00:39:25.496 --> 00:39:29.420
a very simple tool.

00:39:29.420 --> 00:39:34.510
So technology has most
certainly given us

00:39:34.510 --> 00:39:37.490
a whole different
insight into music.

00:39:37.490 --> 00:39:44.430
But the danger, obviously,
is that we tend to pile it on

00:39:44.430 --> 00:39:49.700
so much so that the actual
character of the music

00:39:49.700 --> 00:39:53.680
that we play, the instruments
that we represent,

00:39:53.680 --> 00:39:58.750
kind of take the backseat, and
so a balance has to be found.

00:39:58.750 --> 00:40:01.270
VINOD MARUR: Understood.

00:40:01.270 --> 00:40:05.020
Do you use YouTube yourself
as a distribution mechanism?

00:40:05.020 --> 00:40:07.180
What are your thoughts
on YouTube in terms

00:40:07.180 --> 00:40:08.710
of increasing the reach?

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:10.710
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: Well, first
of all, I'm not tube.

00:40:10.710 --> 00:40:13.320
VINOD MARUR: OK.

00:40:13.320 --> 00:40:14.020
Got it.

00:40:14.020 --> 00:40:14.850
Us [? tube. ?]

00:40:14.850 --> 00:40:16.600
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: That
went like that, right?

00:40:16.600 --> 00:40:17.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:17.270 --> 00:40:17.770
YouTube?

00:40:17.770 --> 00:40:18.540
VINOD MARUR: I got it.

00:40:18.540 --> 00:40:20.456
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: If look
at you and say YouTube,

00:40:20.456 --> 00:40:22.024
you will have to say, no.

00:40:22.024 --> 00:40:24.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:24.980 --> 00:40:28.220
So YouTube, yes.

00:40:28.220 --> 00:40:30.850
So YouTube is a great tool.

00:40:30.850 --> 00:40:31.590
It's amazing.

00:40:31.590 --> 00:40:36.290
I mean, again, there
are discussions

00:40:36.290 --> 00:40:43.370
about whether the artists are
getting the benefit of that

00:40:43.370 --> 00:40:48.540
or in terms of economics, the
financial benefits out of it.

00:40:48.540 --> 00:40:51.420
Most of the artists are not, OK?

00:40:51.420 --> 00:40:53.380
I mean, the other
day we were looking

00:40:53.380 --> 00:40:55.000
at YouTube or
something, and there

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:58.430
was some of my videos,
which had like 600,000

00:40:58.430 --> 00:41:01.380
or some sort of viewership.

00:41:01.380 --> 00:41:04.220
And apparently, there
is a way to go about it

00:41:04.220 --> 00:41:07.320
and be part of it where
royalties come in for that.

00:41:07.320 --> 00:41:09.560
But you have to
go to use so much

00:41:09.560 --> 00:41:14.290
rigmarole to be able to
do that that it's almost

00:41:14.290 --> 00:41:18.370
like you throw up your
hands and say, forget it.

00:41:18.370 --> 00:41:22.280
But YouTube is a great tool
to get music out there,

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:26.320
to get information out there to
people about what you're doing

00:41:26.320 --> 00:41:28.580
and where to come
and see you and where

00:41:28.580 --> 00:41:31.092
to buy tickets and all
that stuff and everything.

00:41:31.092 --> 00:41:32.800
Tweet is another one,
and all that stuff.

00:41:32.800 --> 00:41:39.950
But YouTube gives you a chance
to be able to showcase whatever

00:41:39.950 --> 00:41:42.990
it is that you're going to
be doing, say, in a concert

00:41:42.990 --> 00:41:46.360
or on a concept tour and so
on, so that people can actually

00:41:46.360 --> 00:41:50.920
get some kind of a trailer of
it and be a little bit more

00:41:50.920 --> 00:41:53.410
informed when they
come to see you.

00:41:53.410 --> 00:41:56.940
So in that sense,
YouTube is a great tool.

00:41:56.940 --> 00:42:00.630
For me, it's been great
to be able to hear

00:42:00.630 --> 00:42:04.530
music of the old masters
that has been on YouTube.

00:42:04.530 --> 00:42:08.500
And it's like I wonder, where
did these people find this?

00:42:08.500 --> 00:42:11.710
I mean, there's a lot of
stuff, and I listen to it,

00:42:11.710 --> 00:42:17.130
and that's like gems
that I can learn from,

00:42:17.130 --> 00:42:20.460
that I can take information
from, glean information

00:42:20.460 --> 00:42:25.610
from, and just develop my
repertoire further and further.

00:42:25.610 --> 00:42:29.970
So in that sense for me,
keeping traditional music

00:42:29.970 --> 00:42:35.280
in view and great masters
of that tradition from 1930s

00:42:35.280 --> 00:42:39.400
and '40s and '50s and
their presence on YouTube,

00:42:39.400 --> 00:42:41.650
it has become a
great learning tool.

00:42:41.650 --> 00:42:44.290
So I have to say
that in that sense,

00:42:44.290 --> 00:42:49.471
YouTube has more
positives than negatives.

00:42:49.471 --> 00:42:50.470
VINOD MARUR: Understood.

00:42:50.470 --> 00:42:51.261
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: Yes.

00:42:51.261 --> 00:42:53.410
But obviously, there's
always room for improvement.

00:42:53.410 --> 00:42:54.118
VINOD MARUR: Yes.

00:42:54.118 --> 00:42:55.890
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: But
musicians, I mean,

00:42:55.890 --> 00:43:01.260
whoever runs these
programs or stations should

00:43:01.260 --> 00:43:05.940
try to find a way to make it
possible for the musicians

00:43:05.940 --> 00:43:10.220
to prosper as well
from whatever it is.

00:43:10.220 --> 00:43:12.260
I mean, I'm not
saying that everyone

00:43:12.260 --> 00:43:14.670
is going to be looked
at on YouTube forever.

00:43:14.670 --> 00:43:16.410
I mean, you hear
of people who have

00:43:16.410 --> 00:43:19.010
had two million hits or eight
million hits or something,

00:43:19.010 --> 00:43:23.200
and they are making a decent
amount of money from that.

00:43:23.200 --> 00:43:24.860
But then there are
Indian musicians

00:43:24.860 --> 00:43:29.710
who really have no clue about
how to go about doing that,

00:43:29.710 --> 00:43:33.130
and they just are not
benefiting at all from it.

00:43:33.130 --> 00:43:36.180
So whoever is running
YouTube should

00:43:36.180 --> 00:43:41.500
find a way to be able to be
a little bit more concerned

00:43:41.500 --> 00:43:49.530
as a YouTube helm person
about less fortunate musicians

00:43:49.530 --> 00:43:54.110
who need the help to be
able to keep delivering.

00:43:54.110 --> 00:43:59.450
VINOD MARUR: [INAUDIBLE] I'm
going to skip the next video

00:43:59.450 --> 00:44:01.190
question.

00:44:01.190 --> 00:44:05.190
But roughly, it ties into the
follow-up up question which I

00:44:05.190 --> 00:44:08.200
have for you, which is,
if you look around--

00:44:08.200 --> 00:44:09.880
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: I'm
glad you told me.

00:44:09.880 --> 00:44:11.660
VINOD MARUR: No,
the reason is I know

00:44:11.660 --> 00:44:13.880
they've been eagerly
awaiting this particular one.

00:44:13.880 --> 00:44:17.780
But when you look at
the younger generation,

00:44:17.780 --> 00:44:20.140
there's a sentiment--
whether it's true or not

00:44:20.140 --> 00:44:21.560
is one question I have for you.

00:44:21.560 --> 00:44:24.480
But presuming it's
true, the trend

00:44:24.480 --> 00:44:28.150
seems to be more towards
fusion and away from, I'll say,

00:44:28.150 --> 00:44:31.354
pure classical music.

00:44:31.354 --> 00:44:33.020
First of all, do you
think there is just

00:44:33.020 --> 00:44:37.790
an artificial sentiment, or is
it something real you perceive?

00:44:37.790 --> 00:44:44.460
ZAKIR HUSSAIN: Well,
I feel that there

00:44:44.460 --> 00:44:55.860
is an equal amount of interest
in modern elements of fusion

00:44:55.860 --> 00:44:58.750
and the ancient
elements of fusion.

00:44:58.750 --> 00:45:02.150
And I'm using the word
"fusion" for ancient elements.

00:45:02.150 --> 00:45:04.810
Think about it.

00:45:04.810 --> 00:45:09.220
1,000 years ago in
India there existed

00:45:09.220 --> 00:45:11.200
a music called [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:19.610 --> 00:45:23.330
These were ancient forms
of music, which were

00:45:23.330 --> 00:45:26.010
played in the temples a lot.

00:45:28.660 --> 00:45:32.710
Then came the
Muslims into India.

00:45:32.710 --> 00:45:39.970
And they brought this very
learned Turkish Sufi gentleman

00:45:39.970 --> 00:45:43.690
called Amir Khusrow to India.

00:45:43.690 --> 00:45:53.580
Amir Khusrow was a
master of Qual Qalbana.

00:45:53.580 --> 00:45:58.320
These were Sufi forms of
music now popularly known

00:45:58.320 --> 00:46:03.320
as qawali-- Qual Qalbana,
now known as Qawwali.

00:46:05.960 --> 00:46:11.050
I should pause here and
say Qawwali is actually

00:46:11.050 --> 00:46:17.640
the only seed Sufi
form of music.

00:46:17.640 --> 00:46:21.210
Everything else is a copycat.

00:46:21.210 --> 00:46:23.790
Remember that.

00:46:23.790 --> 00:46:28.110
Amir Khusrow was really
one of those person who

00:46:28.110 --> 00:46:31.460
believes in
universality, humanity

00:46:31.460 --> 00:46:37.380
as being one, religious
elements not being the divider.

00:46:37.380 --> 00:46:42.530
He was really taken by
[INAUDIBLE], [INAUDIBLE],

00:46:42.530 --> 00:46:46.390
and dhrupad singing in
the temples of India.

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:50.670
And he took elements of
those and combined it

00:46:50.670 --> 00:46:54.510
with the Sufi Qual
and Qalbana music.

00:46:54.510 --> 00:46:57.370
And he came up with
a form of music,

00:46:57.370 --> 00:47:04.390
which eventually got known as
or became popular as Khyal.

00:47:04.390 --> 00:47:10.190
Khyal is the premier North
Indian classical form of music

00:47:10.190 --> 00:47:16.260
that anybody from [INAUDIBLE]
or [INAUDIBLE] or [INAUDIBLE]

00:47:16.260 --> 00:47:20.770
or Ravi Shankarji or
[INAUDIBLE], everybody

00:47:20.770 --> 00:47:23.290
plays-- Khyal.

00:47:23.290 --> 00:47:28.380
So fusion already took place
then, already was in place.

00:47:28.380 --> 00:47:29.740
Now imagine this.

00:47:29.740 --> 00:47:35.660
In its seed form, it had its
dos and don't and what to do.

00:47:35.660 --> 00:47:40.910
But over the years, other
elements came into play.

00:47:40.910 --> 00:47:44.690
Musicians moved to different
parts of the country.

00:47:44.690 --> 00:47:47.890
And then they were influenced by
the folk music of that country,

00:47:47.890 --> 00:47:50.100
of that state or that region.

00:47:50.100 --> 00:47:52.770
And that fusion took place.

00:47:52.770 --> 00:47:59.180
And suddenly you started hearing
pahari in classical music

00:47:59.180 --> 00:48:01.990
or you started hearing
kajari or [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:01.990 --> 00:48:05.190
or [INAUDIBLE] or [INAUDIBLE]
into classical music.

00:48:05.190 --> 00:48:07.990
And all this fusion
started to take place.

00:48:07.990 --> 00:48:12.770
So fusion is not something
that is like today.

00:48:12.770 --> 00:48:14.960
It has been going on forever.

00:48:14.960 --> 00:48:16.850
So it's not a new thing.

00:48:16.850 --> 00:48:22.280
So all Indian students of
Indian classical music tradition

00:48:22.280 --> 00:48:26.350
in India are already
sitting on something that

00:48:26.350 --> 00:48:33.170
is a hybrid, a mutated form.

00:48:33.170 --> 00:48:35.420
And so they're playing that.

00:48:35.420 --> 00:48:37.882
Then came the sound
system that changed

00:48:37.882 --> 00:48:39.340
the way the
instruments are played,

00:48:39.340 --> 00:48:42.440
music is played--
another fusion.

00:48:42.440 --> 00:48:43.890
So that has happened.

00:48:43.890 --> 00:48:47.210
So what I'm trying
to say is that when

00:48:47.210 --> 00:48:50.880
you talk about fusion,
you have to understand

00:48:50.880 --> 00:48:54.160
that fusion is already in
Indian classical music.

00:48:54.160 --> 00:48:59.430
Fusion is also considered
the domain of something

00:48:59.430 --> 00:49:02.480
that requires drums
and bass and keyboards

00:49:02.480 --> 00:49:05.590
and whatnot-- no, not true.

00:49:05.590 --> 00:49:12.340
So in 1960s and stuff, I used
to hear Qawwali singers singing

00:49:12.340 --> 00:49:19.490
Qawwali, [INAUDIBLE] players,
tabla players, mandolins,

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:24.870
banjos, all that stuff in
an amplifier or something.

00:49:24.870 --> 00:49:29.230
So even the Sufi music at
that point became fusion.

00:49:29.230 --> 00:49:30.560
So that happened.

00:49:30.560 --> 00:49:35.100
So my understanding of this,
keeping all this in mind,

00:49:35.100 --> 00:49:41.900
is that there is an equal
audience for traditional music

00:49:41.900 --> 00:49:44.440
and the way it's growing.

00:49:44.440 --> 00:49:45.670
It's still changing.

00:49:45.670 --> 00:49:47.650
It's still mutating.

00:49:47.650 --> 00:49:49.890
So that's what's
happening with it.

00:49:49.890 --> 00:49:54.120
And then there's the fusion
known as fusion world

00:49:54.120 --> 00:49:54.960
these days.

00:49:54.960 --> 00:50:00.140
Like for instance, I played with
[INAUDIBLE] in Civic San Jose.

00:50:00.140 --> 00:50:02.100
He sang [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:02.100 --> 00:50:04.570
[INAUDIBLE] is an old form.

00:50:04.570 --> 00:50:08.550
But he had a guitar player,
he had a keyboard player,

00:50:08.550 --> 00:50:12.670
he had me playing
tabla, and I also

00:50:12.670 --> 00:50:16.910
had some kind of a
drum set-up thing.

00:50:16.910 --> 00:50:18.700
So he's singing [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:18.700 --> 00:50:20.340
That is the form
that's going on.

00:50:20.340 --> 00:50:24.000
What you have done
is you've put more

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:29.640
today's rhythmic and melodic,
harmonic ideas onto it.

00:50:29.640 --> 00:50:32.350
But the core
element is the same.

00:50:32.350 --> 00:50:35.790
So whether that is fusion
or not, I don't know.

00:50:35.790 --> 00:50:38.560
So the core element is the same.

00:50:38.560 --> 00:50:41.880
Where fusion
appeared in Bollywood

00:50:41.880 --> 00:50:49.520
was way back in 1940s when
music directors started using

00:50:49.520 --> 00:50:52.070
violins and cellos and whatnot.

00:50:52.070 --> 00:50:55.580
I remember playing recordings
for music composers

00:50:55.580 --> 00:51:00.320
like [INAUDIBLE] or [INAUDIBLE]
or [INAUDIBLE] or Shanker

00:51:00.320 --> 00:51:01.860
Jaikishan and so on.

00:51:01.860 --> 00:51:04.230
I grew up in that world.

00:51:04.230 --> 00:51:06.250
And we'd be in that room.

00:51:06.250 --> 00:51:11.730
Believe it or not, the room
was probably 10% of this size,

00:51:11.730 --> 00:51:14.120
just like one angle like this.

00:51:14.120 --> 00:51:19.730
And at one end, there were
two tables, tabla, dholak,

00:51:19.730 --> 00:51:23.930
and a couple of chairs,
[INAUDIBLE] wallah and shaker

00:51:23.930 --> 00:51:28.320
wallah -- ch-ch-ch-- that
stuff, and one microphone

00:51:28.320 --> 00:51:29.710
in the middle, OK?

00:51:29.710 --> 00:51:31.890
So if they wanted to hear
more of my bass drum,

00:51:31.890 --> 00:51:34.465
they'd say, move the bass
drum a little forward.

00:51:34.465 --> 00:51:35.830
[LAUGHTER]

00:51:35.830 --> 00:51:38.230
There wasn't adjustment
in the booth.

00:51:38.230 --> 00:51:40.450
You had to adjust it yourself.

00:51:40.450 --> 00:51:41.900
So that was the thing.

00:51:41.900 --> 00:51:45.720
Then just directly across from
me at the other end of the room

00:51:45.720 --> 00:51:50.680
were about 35, 40 chairs,
violins, violas, cellos.

00:51:50.680 --> 00:51:52.640
They were all laid out.

00:51:52.640 --> 00:51:56.670
On the left of
them were the bass.

00:51:56.670 --> 00:51:59.360
Left of the bass was the piano.

00:51:59.360 --> 00:52:02.860
On opposite side of the
piano was another microphone,

00:52:02.860 --> 00:52:05.420
and around that
microphone on tables

00:52:05.420 --> 00:52:09.020
raised sat cross-legged
[INAUDIBLE]

00:52:09.020 --> 00:52:13.840
on flute, Sultan Khan on
sarangi, Rais Khan on sitar.

00:52:13.840 --> 00:52:15.600
They all sat over there.

00:52:15.600 --> 00:52:19.920
And all of us-- and
including the horn players,

00:52:19.920 --> 00:52:23.180
who were between the [INAUDIBLE]
rhythm players and the violin,

00:52:23.180 --> 00:52:25.590
standing in the
center with saxophone,

00:52:25.590 --> 00:52:30.190
trumpet, trombone, all
that, they were there.

00:52:30.190 --> 00:52:35.360
And we are all playing for
a song sung in the booth

00:52:35.360 --> 00:52:38.870
by [INAUDIBLE] or
[INAUDIBLE] and so on.

00:52:38.870 --> 00:52:43.710
And in those days, you had
to play the song through.

00:52:43.710 --> 00:52:46.340
If somebody made a
mistake, you stop,

00:52:46.340 --> 00:52:48.760
and you did it all over again.

00:52:48.760 --> 00:52:52.880
These days, you can sing one
word, stop, sing two words,

00:52:52.880 --> 00:52:55.750
stop, sing a line, stop.

00:52:55.750 --> 00:52:59.600
And not just that--
sing one word 500 times,

00:52:59.600 --> 00:53:03.040
sing two words 1,000
times and so on

00:53:03.040 --> 00:53:05.270
and on and then pick the best.

00:53:05.270 --> 00:53:06.190
It wasn't like that.

00:53:06.190 --> 00:53:08.980
But that was also fusion.

00:53:08.980 --> 00:53:11.730
And so fusion started
way back then.

00:53:11.730 --> 00:53:14.180
And then RD Burman took
it to a different level.

00:53:14.180 --> 00:53:16.990
LP took it to a different level.

00:53:16.990 --> 00:53:19.580
Bappi Lahiri brought it
down to a different level.

00:53:19.580 --> 00:53:23.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:23.910 --> 00:53:25.560
And so on and on happened.

00:53:25.560 --> 00:53:30.980
But all I'm trying to say
is that you heard fusion

00:53:30.980 --> 00:53:32.830
in Madan Mohan's song.

00:53:32.830 --> 00:53:34.920
And they were some of
the most beautiful songs

00:53:34.920 --> 00:53:36.730
that you will ever hear.

00:53:36.730 --> 00:53:40.590
You heard some of the great old
songs of Laxmikant Pyarelal--

00:53:40.590 --> 00:53:42.720
fabulous.

00:53:42.720 --> 00:53:47.970
[NON-ENGLISH SINGING]

00:54:05.230 --> 00:54:07.625
One of the earlier songs
of LP-- I played it.

00:54:07.625 --> 00:54:11.770
[APPLAUSE]

00:54:11.770 --> 00:54:14.950
So these kind of songs
were already there.

00:54:14.950 --> 00:54:17.550
So fusion is good.

00:54:17.550 --> 00:54:19.190
Fusion is acceptable.

00:54:19.190 --> 00:54:22.320
Fusion is the next wave.

00:54:22.320 --> 00:54:24.560
And when you say
the next wave, it's

00:54:24.560 --> 00:54:26.790
not like for the
next six months.

00:54:26.790 --> 00:54:30.090
It's been there for the
last 15, 20, 30 years.

00:54:30.090 --> 00:54:34.810
And it will go on until somebody
finds another word-- refusion

00:54:34.810 --> 00:54:40.160
or defusion or C-fusion
or confusion or whatever.

00:54:40.160 --> 00:54:42.850
They'll find words
that will be different.

00:54:42.850 --> 00:54:47.120
When John McLaughlin and I
and L. Shankar on the violin

00:54:47.120 --> 00:54:50.040
and Vikku Vinayakram on the
ghatam got together and played

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:52.940
a band called Shakti
and we recorded--

00:54:52.940 --> 00:54:54.710
[APPLAUSE]

00:54:54.710 --> 00:54:55.660
You can clap.

00:54:55.660 --> 00:54:56.220
It's OK.

00:54:56.220 --> 00:54:58.090
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:58.090 --> 00:55:01.070
I'll act properly demure and--

00:55:01.070 --> 00:55:02.200
[LAUGHTER]

00:55:02.200 --> 00:55:05.670
Anyway, so when we played
and the recording was made,

00:55:05.670 --> 00:55:11.020
the head of CBS, Clive
Davis, says to John, John,

00:55:11.020 --> 00:55:13.720
what should we call this?

00:55:13.720 --> 00:55:14.720
John said, I don't know.

00:55:14.720 --> 00:55:15.320
Zakir?

00:55:15.320 --> 00:55:16.810
I said, I don't know.

00:55:16.810 --> 00:55:18.360
It's music.

00:55:18.360 --> 00:55:20.680
We had no clue
what we were doing.

00:55:20.680 --> 00:55:21.730
For us it was just music.

00:55:21.730 --> 00:55:23.780
It wasn't like a little
of jazz, a little

00:55:23.780 --> 00:55:25.470
of Indian, a little
of South Indian

00:55:25.470 --> 00:55:27.780
and some Qawwali
rhythms and all that

00:55:27.780 --> 00:55:31.200
and let's call it
"confusion"-- none of that.

00:55:31.200 --> 00:55:32.430
We had no clue.

00:55:32.430 --> 00:55:34.840
For us it was just music.

00:55:34.840 --> 00:55:39.460
So when musicians get together
to play from different genres,

00:55:39.460 --> 00:55:43.330
they don't think that they
are creating a particular kind

00:55:43.330 --> 00:55:45.350
of fusion music.

00:55:45.350 --> 00:55:47.310
They're creating music.

00:55:47.310 --> 00:55:49.580
They're doing a
creative process, which

00:55:49.580 --> 00:55:51.920
they are enjoying and so on.

00:55:51.920 --> 00:55:53.860
But Clive Davis says,
but John, I really

00:55:53.860 --> 00:55:56.680
need to know what to
call it, because then I

00:55:56.680 --> 00:56:02.840
can label it and put it in the
right bin in Tower Records.

00:56:02.840 --> 00:56:07.060
And then we can also put
it in the right category

00:56:07.060 --> 00:56:10.190
for the Billboards
award or whatever.

00:56:10.190 --> 00:56:12.770
So they needed to
make a category.

00:56:12.770 --> 00:56:14.720
So when we started
doing that, there

00:56:14.720 --> 00:56:16.560
wasn't even a word fusion.

00:56:16.560 --> 00:56:19.700
There wasn't even a word
New Age or anything.

00:56:19.700 --> 00:56:22.130
When Madan Mohan did his
songs or Shanker Jaikishan

00:56:22.130 --> 00:56:25.010
did his song, there was no
"fusion" word or anything.

00:56:25.010 --> 00:56:26.870
But it was all happening.

00:56:26.870 --> 00:56:28.960
And it started way back then.

00:56:28.960 --> 00:56:32.910
So whether it's China,
Japan, you name it,

00:56:32.910 --> 00:56:36.190
they all have influences from
different parts of the world

00:56:36.190 --> 00:56:39.360
wherever the Raj went--
I mean British Raj--

00:56:39.360 --> 00:56:41.666
and wherever the French went.

00:56:41.666 --> 00:56:43.290
They all brought
whatever they brought,

00:56:43.290 --> 00:56:45.120
and it just kind of made it.

00:56:45.120 --> 00:56:49.700
So now what's happened,
which I like very much,

00:56:49.700 --> 00:56:54.300
is that the lines are
blurred, blurred in the sense

00:56:54.300 --> 00:56:58.080
that it used to be that
fusion music can only

00:56:58.080 --> 00:57:00.630
be in the Western world.

00:57:00.630 --> 00:57:02.390
And so it was legit.

00:57:02.390 --> 00:57:04.560
But now, people
all over the world

00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:09.020
are able to make music,
whether it's in Mali or Senegal

00:57:09.020 --> 00:57:15.230
or in Mauritius or
in Tokyo or wherever,

00:57:15.230 --> 00:57:17.360
and they are all
playing music, which

00:57:17.360 --> 00:57:24.170
has an interesting drive
towards universality.

00:57:24.170 --> 00:57:26.530
Instruments are common.

00:57:26.530 --> 00:57:28.830
Thought processes are common.

00:57:28.830 --> 00:57:31.680
And people are
starting to make music,

00:57:31.680 --> 00:57:33.440
whether it's Japan
or China or India

00:57:33.440 --> 00:57:40.110
or whatever, that stands on
its own anywhere in the world.

00:57:40.110 --> 00:57:42.560
And Bollywood is a
great example of it.

